By data I meant the underlying data model of the document
type itself.

If you have an entity of Content-Type: text/xml:

  &lt;test   attr1 = &quot;foo&quot;   attr2=&quot;bar&quot;   /&gt;

and you claim that the whitespace is significant,
then strictly speaking you don&#39;t really have an XML
document anymore.

So if you PUT the above element with Content-Type of
text/xml then GETting back

  &lt;test attr1=&quot;foo&quot; attr2=&quot;bar&quot;/&gt;

has to be okay.  If the space is significant then
use text/plain, the server may reject it.  If PUT
demands that even with a known type of XML, that
byte-for-byte fidelity be maintained, then the
semantics are pathological to the point of not
being useable except for storing files.

Similarly if you further refine the type to being say,
an RSS 2.0 document, then whitespace text nodes, for
example between &lt;item&gt; elements, or between the &lt;rss&gt;
and &lt;channel&gt; elements aren&#39;t significant, so lossily
storing those documents has to be okay too.

If this isn&#39;t true, I&#39;d like to understand why.

- Jeff








