&gt; From: &quot;Jeffrey Winter&quot; &lt;JeffreyWinter@...&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I&#39;ve been working with the Tamino WebDAV Server and
&gt; &gt; found that its implementation of PUT stores the
&gt; &gt; entity using the XML infoset and not a byte-for-byte
&gt; &gt; copy. For example, PUT-ing:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;   &lt;test&gt;&lt;/test&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; will be retrieved using GET as:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;   &lt;test/&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I know this issue has come up several times on this
&gt; &gt; list, but it is interesting to see that one major vendor
&gt; &gt; at least has interpreted the semantics of PUT in a data-centric
&gt; &gt; way as opposed to a document-centric way.  I tend to agree
&gt; &gt; with their approach as it makes PUT much more useful.
&gt;
&gt; I don&#39;t think this is a document-vs-data thing.  I think that this is a
&gt; semantics-vs-syntax thing.  Since &quot;&lt;test&gt;&lt;/test&gt;&quot; and &quot;&lt;test/&gt;&quot; are
&gt; semantically equivalent, an xml parser *should* handle the document
exactly
&gt; the same way.
&gt;
&gt; And yes, I (imho) think this attitude makes PUT much more powerful without
&gt; crippling it&#39;s functionality.  I think that any client application that
&gt; would choke on receiving &quot;&lt;test/&gt;&quot; instead of &quot;&lt;test&gt;&lt;/test&gt;&quot; would
indicate
&gt; a badly designed client, not a badly designed server.
